@ event.target;  //the "target" returns the element where the event is happening. (But just works with the .addEventListener method.

Example:

<h1>Click Me!</h1>
<script>
  let h1 = document.getElementsByTagName('h1')[0];
  h1.addEventListener('click', changeH1);
  
  function seeTheEvent(event){
    console.log(event);
    console.log(event.target);
    }
</script>

>>> MouseEvent (etc..) //this is the console.log(event) - it will show the event itself.
>>> <h1>Click Me!</h1> //this is the console.log(event.target) - it will show the element that the event happened.
